\begin_layout Standard
Consider the system of differential equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx}{dt}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & 2\\
 & a
\end{array}\right)x
\]

\end_inset

with initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
3\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For what value(s) of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 will the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 approach a nonzero constant vector at large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 from the previous part, write down the exact solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 (at all times, not just for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To make the ODE solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=e^{At}$
\end_inset

 go to a nonzero constant, we want one 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\lambda t}$
\end_inset

 term to be constant (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

) and the other 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\lambda t}$
\end_inset

 term to be decaying (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\operatorname{Re}(\lambda)<0$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & 2\\
 & a
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an upper-triangular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A-\lambda I$
\end_inset

) is just the product of the diagonals 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1-\lambda)(a-\lambda)$
\end_inset

 and the eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=a$
\end_inset

.
 The first eigenvalue gives decaying solutions, so we need 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{a=0}$
\end_inset

 to get a constant solution from the other term.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Technically, we also need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)$
\end_inset

 has a nonzero coefficient of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 eigenvector, but we will verify this in part (b).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

, we need to (1) expand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)$
\end_inset

 in the basis of eigenvectors and (2) multiply each term by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\lambda t}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, we are looking for the solution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=e^{At}x(0)=\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
x_{1} & x_{2}\end{array}\right)}_{X}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
e^{-t}\\
 & e^{0t}
\end{array}\right)}_{e^{\Lambda t}}\underbrace{X^{-1}x(0)}_{c}=c_{1}e^{-t}x_{1}+c_{2}x_{2},
\]

\end_inset

which corresponds to expanding a solution in the basis of the eigenvectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

, finding the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)$
\end_inset

, and multiplying each term by the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\lambda t}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

First, we need to 
\emph on
find
\emph default
 the eigenvectors, but this a straightforward exercise in computing nullspaces
 (which in this simple case can be done by inspection): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A-\cancelto{-1}{\lambda_{1}}I)x_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 2\\
 & 1
\end{array}\right)x_{1}=\vec{0}\implies x_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A-\cancelto{0}{\lambda_{2}}I)x_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & 2\\
 & 0
\end{array}\right)x_{2}=\vec{0}\implies x_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now, to expand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)$
\end_inset

 this basis, we write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(0)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
3\\
1
\end{array}\right)=c_{1}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right)}_{x_{1}}+c_{2}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right)}_{x_{2}}=\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 2\\
 & 1
\end{array}\right)}_{X}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}
\end{array}\right)}_{c}\implies c=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which is solvable by inspection, or by using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is upper-triangular so we can do backsubstitution (with no elimination
 steps).
 (If we wrote the eigenvalues in the opposite order we would have gotten
 a lower-triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, from which we could do forward-substitution.) Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=c_{1}e^{\lambda_{1}t}x_{1}+c_{2}e^{\lambda_{2}t}x_{2}=e^{-t}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right)+e^{0t}\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right)=\boxed{\left(\begin{array}{c}
2+e^{-t}\\
1
\end{array}\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which clearly approaches the nonzero constant vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 as desired in part (a), since 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}\ne0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

