\begin_layout Subsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The key thing is to realize that we just need 
\emph on
any 
\emph default
nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp x_{1}$
\end_inset

, for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\left(\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
0\\
1\\
0
\end{array}\right)}$
\end_inset

 works.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian, any eigenvector for eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\ne\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp x_{1}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 in the orthogonal complement of the span of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, which is 4-dimensional.
 Since 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 of the other eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, the eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 must have multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 (there are 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 eigenvalues in total, counting repeated roots) and there must be 4 eigenvectors
 for that eigenvalue — together with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, they must form a 
\emph on
basis
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{5}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian therefore diagonalizable).
 So, the eigenvectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 must be the 
\emph on
whole
\emph default
 4-dimensional subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp x_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The projection onto 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\frac{x_{1}x_{1}^{T}}{x_{1}^{T}x_{1}}b=x_{1}\frac{\cancelto{7}{x_{1}^{T}b}}{\cancelto{7}{x_{1}^{T}x_{1}}}=\boxed{x_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2\\
-1\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that, as usual it would be equivalent but 
\emph on
much 
\emph default
more work to first compute the 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 rank-1 projection matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\frac{x_{1}x_{1}^{T}}{x_{1}^{T}x_{1}}=\frac{1}{7}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & -1 & 0 & 1\\
2 & 4 & -2 & 0 & 2\\
-1 & -2 & 1 & 0 & -1\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
1 & 2 & -1 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 and then multiply it by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Parentheses make a big practical difference in linear algebra! The projection
 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=(I-P)b=b-p=b-x_{1}=\boxed{\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

Again, it would be a lot more work to first compute 
\begin_inset Formula $I-P=\frac{1}{7}\begin{pmatrix}6 & -2 & 1 & 0 & -1\\
-2 & 3 & 2 & 0 & -2\\
1 & 2 & 6 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 7 & 0\\
-1 & -2 & 1 & 0 & 6
\end{pmatrix}$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
then
\emph default
 multiply it by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as the sum of the two projections, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=p+e$
\end_inset

, and notice that the first term 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and the second term is in the orthogonal complement and hence (from part
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

a) an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
 So,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{n}b=\lambda_{1}^{n}p+1^{n}e=\boxed{\frac{1}{(-2)^{n}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2\\
-1\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

